As the market has seen in the past about a month, waiting for an interest rate raise can make the situation unstable.
When the increase becomes a fact, the effect is not quite so dramatic.
"It seems that return on capital tends to stagnate for 12-24 months after the first increase, which again potentially reflects a delay in monetary policy," Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study of what happens after the central bank increase.
More specifically, in the last 35 years or so, the market tends to be strong, with an increase of about 14% when approaching the increase, 250 days after that the situation is fairly steady (average increase of 2.6%), and the normal state has been reached after 500 days with an average return of 14.4% in the last six cycles, according to a recent analysis by senior capital strategist Bob Doll of Nuvee Asset Management.
