The nematodes normally do not react to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that when surrounded by a liquid with microscopic bubbles, the situation changed.
He found that the bubbles amplified the ultrasonic waves, which then pass inside the worms.
Amplified ultrasound waves affect TRP-4 ion channels, structures found in the cell membranes of some worms.
Sound waves cause these ion channels to open and activate the cells attached to them, according to a report published in Nature Communications.
To produce ultrasound-controlled nematodes, Chalasani genetically modified the nematodes so that some of their motion nerve cells have TRP-4 ion channels.
When Chalasani used ultrasound on modified worms, the microbubbles amplified the sound waves and transmitted them to the worms, where they switch on the modified motion nerve cells.
The method has some of the same features as optogenetics, a ground-breaking tool that allows scientists to turn on and off neurons using light impulses.
However, Chalasani says that the use of sonogenetics may have some advantages over optogenetics.
Unlike light, which must be sent along the optical fiber to a desired location inside the brain, low-frequency ultrasound waves can pass through the tissue unhindered, so they can be sent to the brain from the top of the skull.
"We believe that by using gene therapy and therapeutic virus, it may be possible for target human nerve cells to temporarily respond to ultrasound signals in certain neurological treatments in a clinical setting," Chalasani said.
Other applications could focus on muscle cells and insulin-producing cells, he added.
