This week, the Federal Reserve is sitting for two days on a huge mahogany table at a long-awaited meeting to decide whether it is time to raise the key rate for the first time in almost a decade.
At the other end of the central bank’s decorative, two-storey meeting room is a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that central bank president Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues must put the nation’s economic interests first.
Congress has placed a dual responsibility on the central bank: to maximize US employment and keep prices stable.
After the Great Recession, however, the governors of the central bank have accepted that there is also a third, unwritten mandate: financial stability.
This third requirement could be the decisive factor in the decision to be announced on Thursday, which is so strict that it cannot even be predicted, whether the US economy is ready to be weaned from the record short-term stimulus brought about by the near-zero level of interest rates since the end of 2008.
While most of the data shows steady economic growth, the recent turbulence in global financial markets may have made central bank officials, who are already on guard, even more frightened when it comes to increasing volatility. There are fears about what the effect would be if the federal funds rate was raised by even a quarter.
"Understandably, the labour market and inflation are the first and most important factors to be monitored," says Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economics specialist at Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"I believe, however, that if they are looking for justification for keeping interest rates unchanged, increased uncertainty in the global market is a valid enough reason to wait," he said.
There has been no agreement on the Central Bank's decision, which is already causing nervousness in the economy.
According to a recent study by Bloomberg, about half of economists predict that interest rates will rise this week.
The financial markets, on the other hand, expect the central bank to delay the increase, as the key indicator shows that the chance of growth is only around 30%.
This suggests a fall in the securities market if the central bank raises the level, unless the policymakers then manage to soften the shock by promising that the next raise will not take place in the near future.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose by 228.89 points, or 1.4 per cent, the new figure being 16,599.85.
The recovery was accompanied by the expectation that the central bank would maintain its level this week, says John Lonski, chief economics officer at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
“It’s surprising if the central bank raises interest rates right now,” he says.
If policymakers raise interest rates, “they will have to put a lot of effort into their policy to support the financial markets so that they don’t panic.”
Other experts argue that an elevated level would calm the financial markets because it would remove uncertainty as to when the central bank will operate.
Just a month ago, it seemed that the central bank would be raising interest rates by a quarter of a percentage point this month, thus taking the first small step towards a slow tightening of the monetary situation that would ensure the stability of the US recovery.
Yellen has stated in the spring and early summer that he expects the level to rise this year despite the fact that the Liberals are calling for more economic development in their elections.
Although job creation slowed down in August, labour market growth has been stable this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest figure in seven years and close to what the central bank regards as the threshold for full employment.
Wage growth has shown signs of recovery.
While inflation is still below the central bank’s 2% annual target, the central bank’s decision-makers say the main reason for this is the temporary effect of the substantially lower oil price.
The economy “can cope with even higher interest rates and needs them in view of the tight labour market conditions,” says Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, the global financial markets were shaken last week when China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell by 16 percent from its May record, with investors fearing that China’s slowing economy would also slow global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, and the Dow index is now nearly 10 percent below its peak in May.
For central bank policy makers, market turmoil is an additional factor in a complex equation that tells when interest rates should be raised.
"Without these financial market events and the news of recent weeks about China's economic weakness, policymakers would tighten the tide at this meeting," said Stephen D. Oliner, a specialist at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former central bank official.
Now he predicts that policymakers will wait at least a month to get a better idea of the effects.
"The potential impact on the U.S. economy is still rather unclear, and they have little information at their disposal about the consequences of what happened in China," Oliner said.
The well-being of the international economy is not the central bank’s main concern, so in principle it should not influence decision-making.
In practice, however, the Federal Reserve has become the world’s monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the central bank has been enormous.
In 2013, a suggestion by the then president, Ben S. Bernanke, that the central bank could “restrict” the increase in the amount of money, caused turbulence in markets around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, central bank officials are expected not only to monitor developments elsewhere, but also to consult other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
The central bank’s decision-making process is “more an art than a science,” says Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Virginia, pointed out this month that “the central bank has previously overreacted to financial market movements that seem to be separated from economic fundamentals.”
The decision-making Federal Open Market Committee has called for interest rates to be raised, and Lacker, a member of the Committee entitled to vote, is citing the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
The Asian economic crisis caused the central bank to cut its benchmark by 0.75 percentage points over three meetings “despite its limited, recognisable impact on U.S. economic growth,” Lacker says.
A year later, the central bank reversed these cuts.
The central bank should only prioritise financial stability during a major crisis, such as when the markets collapsed in 2008, says Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate setting committee.
The latest turmoil will not come close to its level, Posen says.
"Nobody wants a situation where there is fear of a rise in interest rates because the market is getting upset," said Posen, chairman of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains a dual requirement and does not mention financial stability; as long as this is the case, I do not think they should anticipate it.
