Weight Loss Surgery May Help Slightly Obese Diabetics
According to a new study, the benefits of weight loss surgery for mildly obese type 2 diabetics can last for at least five years.
However, it is still too early to say whether these mildly obese diabetics will live longer after a weight loss surgery than those who are treated in ways other than surgery.
"It takes a long time to get mortality data," says Dr. Robin Blackstone, a weight loss surgery specialist who wrote an editorial for a new study in the journal JAMA Surgery.
In bariatric surgery, different methods are used to reduce the size of the abdomen.
They reduce hunger and limit the absorption of food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been shown to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most of the participants in the study have been morbidly obese and have a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or more.
BMI is considered normal when it is between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI above 25 indicates that someone is overweight, and a person with a BMI above 30 is considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For this new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery, gastric bypass surgery, and gastric reduction, with type 2 diabetes medications for people who were slightly obese.
The study showed that the average BMI of the surgical subjects decreased from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year.
At the same time, people treated with non-surgical methods had a BMI that remained roughly the same at 29.
Of the surgical subjects, 36 percent had a complete and 28 percent partial improvement in diabetes.
By comparison, in the drug-treated group, diabetes was completely cured by only 1% and partially cured by about 2%.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides, and the “bad” LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgical group,” the authors noted.
The researchers also monitored the patients’ blood levels of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood sugar levels over the long term.
Hemoglobin A1c should remain below 7%, the researchers write.
Post-operative hemoglobin A1c levels dropped from about 9% to about 6%.
In the medical treatment group, however, it remained stable at about 8%.
However, this improved “glycemic control,” as demonstrated by improved hemoglobin A1c levels, did not reduce mortality over five years, says lead researcher Dr Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The study group also compared the average results between two different types of surgery.
At the fifth year, compared to the group undergoing gastric bypass surgery, the group undergoing gastric bypass surgery had lost more weight (18.7 and 14.2 kg), had decreased its BMI more (7.4 and 5.1), had decreased haemoglobin A1c more than its levels (3.1 and 2.1 %), and was more likely to have achieved complete diabetes remission (46.9 and 16.7 %).
Blackstone, of the University of Arizona College of Medicine-Phoenix, says that while the study shows no survival or surgery after five years, there are research findings from Sweden where surgery led to longer lives in heavier people.
A Swedish study found that obese people undergoing weight loss surgery were 29 percent less likely to die over a 15-year period when compared to a group that had tried more traditional treatments.
While the new study does not show any improvement in surgical survival, Blackstone says the results are encouraging for people with a BMI below 35 who are interested in surgery.
"The findings are decisive in that they show that surgery is safe for a group with a lower BMI," he says, "and not associated with an increased risk of death or kidney disease."
Blackstone adds that both patients and their doctors should take weight very seriously when a patient has a BMI between 27 and 30.
“I think we’ll wait too long before we take this seriously,” he says.
I believe that when a person has accumulated these genetic changes that permanently prepare his body for obesity and diabetes, it is very difficult to reverse the situation.
