Xi Calls for Opening the Economy to the World
The economy needs to be more open to the outside world to promote growth, President Xi Jinping told a group whose task is to lead the reform.
"China should commit to attracting foreign finance and expertise and developing a policy of transparency," he said, speaking at the 16th meeting of the Group on Deepening the General Reform.
Supporting transparency at the same time as pushing reforms forward adds new movement and vitality, as well as creating new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The Steering Board adopted a series of guidelines, including a negative list limiting market access, loosening of border control principles, urging state-owned enterprises to take up private capital, and a review of the resident registration system.
According to the opinion, a negative list will be created, identifying the sectors and companies in which investment is not allowed.
The system will be tested gradually and improved through pilot programmes.
The change is significant as it gives the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensures a legally-based business environment and makes the market more open.
The government also loosens control over the power it distributes to companies, thereby ensuring that companies themselves decide how to run their business.
It also said that China would allow border regions to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms for developing regional growth.
More sectors will be opened up to private investors to open up government-dominated sectors.
"The government will not change its policy on foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide them with better services," the statement said.
In addition, the application process for foreign permanent residents, "green cards", will be facilitated by optimising the requirements and simplifying the application process.
The meeting also discussed the guarantee of professional rights for lawyers and support for professional judges and prosecutors.
The meeting was also attended by Prime Minister Li Keqiang and senior leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, according to a statement published after the meeting.
